SIMPLE: minister
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Minister
<hw>Min"is*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>ministre</ets>, F. <ets>ministre</ets>, fr. L. <ets>minister</ets>,
orig. a double comparative from the root of <ets>minor</ets> less, and
hence meaning, an inferior, a servant. See 1st <er>Minor</er>, and cf.
<er>Master</er>, <er>Minstrel</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A servant; a subordinate; an officer or assistant of
inferior rank; hence, an agent, an instrument.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Moses rose up, and his <qex>minister</qex> Joshua.</q>
<rj><qau>Ex. xxiv. 13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I chose⟦br⟧
Camillo for the <qex>minister</qex>, to poison⟦br⟧
My friend Polixenes.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An officer of justice.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I cry out the on the <qex>ministres</qex>, quod he,⟦br⟧
That shoulde keep and rule this cit⟦eacute⟧.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One to whom the sovereign or executive head of a
government intrusts the management of affairs of state, or some
department of such affairs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Ministers</qex> to kings, whose eyes, ears, and hands they
are, must be answerable to God and man.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A representative of a government, sent to the court,
or seat of government, of a foreign nation to transact diplomatic
business.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Ambassadors are classed (in the diplomatic sense) in the
first rank of public ministers, ministers plenipotentiary in the second.
⟦ldquo⟧The United States diplomatic service employs two classes of
ministers, -- ministers plenipotentiary and ministers
resident.⟦rdquo⟧</note> <rj><au>Abbott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>One who serves at the altar; one who performs
sacerdotal duties; the pastor of a church duly authorized or licensed to
preach the gospel and administer the sacraments.</def>
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Delegate; official; ambassador; clergyman;
parson; priest.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minister</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Minister
<hw>Min"is*ter</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Ministered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Ministering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>ministren</ets>,
OF. <ets>ministrer</ets>, fr. L. <ets>ministrare</ets>. See
<er>Minister</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To furnish or apply; to
afford; to supply; to administer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that <qex>ministereth</qex> seed to the sower.</q> <rj><qau>2
Cor. ix. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We <qex>minister</qex> to God reason to suspect us.</q>
<rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Minister</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Minister
<hw>Min"is*ter</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To act as a
servant, attendant, or agent; to attend and serve; to perform service in
any office, sacred or secular.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Son of man came not to be <qex>ministered</qex> unto, but to
<qex>minister</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. xx. 28.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To supply or to things needful; esp., to supply
consolation or remedies; <as>as, to <ex>minister</ex> to the
sick</as>.</def> <rj><au>Matt. xxv. 44.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Canst thou not <qex>minister</qex> to a mind diseased?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ministerial</ent>⟦br⟧
